{"id":"1905.00733","submitter":"Nirupam Gupta","authors":"Nirupam Gupta and Nikhil Chopra","title":"Privacy of Agents' Costs in Peer-to-Peer Distributed Optimization","comments":"arXiv admin note: text overlap with arXiv:1809.01794,\n  arXiv:1903.09315","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.SY","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In this paper, we propose a protocol that preserves (statistical) privacy of\nagents' costs in peer-to-peer distributed optimization against a passive\nadversary that corrupts certain number of agents in the network. The proposed\nprotocol guarantees privacy of the affine parts of the honest agents' costs\n(agents that are not corrupted by the adversary) if the corrupted agents do not\nform a vertex cut of the underlying communication topology. Therefore, if the\n(passive) adversary corrupts at most t arbitrary agents in the network then the\nproposed protocol can preserve the privacy of the affine parts of the remaining\nhonest agents' costs if the communication topology has (t+1)-connectivity. The\nproposed privacy protocol is a composition of a privacy mechanism (we propose)\nwith any (non-private) distributed optimization algorithm.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 1 May 2019 16:13:07 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-05-03"}
